As the dominant indicator, the LULC of the NSTM exhibited a north–south gradient pattern of divergence, with glaciers, forests, grasslands, construction land, cultivated land, and unused land ranking from south to north (Fig. E1 in Appendix E). The LULC changed significantly during the study period (Table 3
                        ). Among them, unused land and grassland were the major types, with the sum of their areas reaching approximately 80 %. Cultivated land increased from 12.4 % to 17.0 %, and built-up land increased from 1.3 % to 2.4 %, which demonstrated the excellent achievements of agricultural development and urban construction during 2005–2020. Undeniably, forests, water, and wetlands decreased with varying magnitudes. From a temporal perspective (Fig. 4
                        ), land use change in 2005–2020 was more active than that in 2010–2020, both in terms of region expansion and reduction. Furthermore, the areas of the LULC classifications that decreased in 2005–2020 were greater than those of the classifications that increased, while the opposite was true in 2010–2020.
